# Choosing a Scheme Implementation #

Nostalgia and a mild case of insomnia has led to me chase links on the
web.  I fell in love with Scheme the very first time my 61A professor
rolled in his relic of a terminal and displayed typed in those simple
prefix notation expressions.  Unfortunately, that was the first and
last class for any Lisp dialect.  I thought I'd learn a little more so
I could appreciate this darling language more.  But to do that, I'd
need to pick an implemenation to play around with.

[Scheme R6RS](http://www.r6rs.org/) is the official design and
implemenation specification for the language.  I'm going though the
list of implemenations found at
[schemers](http://community.schemewiki.org/?scheme-faq-standards#implementations)
to find one to play with.  The most important features to me are good
documentation, comprehensive libraries and active community.  Since
R6RS has been out for almost a year, I'll only list implementations
that make a mention of it to ensure they're still being actively
developed.  Common features I notice about the implementations are
that some of them compile to another target language such as C, and
some of them are intended to be embedded languages rather than general
purpose programming environments.

